      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The originalist approach is undeniably the most grounded in the actual text and historical context of the founding era. Those who advocate for this view correctly point out that the Constitution is a fixed document, not a malleable text subject to modern social trends. The counter-argument often involves a selective reading of history, whereas originalism demands a rigorous adherence to the meaning understood by the ratifiers. Therefore, originalism provides the most coherent and legally defensible framework for interpreting the Founders' intent.",
